ers, jazz musicians, and sex workers. Through their stories, Cigarettes, Inc. accounts for the cigarette's spectacular rise in popularity and in the process offers nothing less than a sweeping reinterpretation of corporate power itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCigarette industryzChinaxHistory. 0aCigarette industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aChina. 4aUnited States. 4abright leaf tobaco. 4acigarette. 4acorporation. 4aempire. 4aglobal. 4amodernity. 4asegregation. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226533452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226533452.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles